X-FileName: sscott5 (Non-Privileged).Berilac Brandybuck & Last Mountain Entreprises (DRAM-uh-turj) noun, also dramaturge or dramaturgist

   1. A playwright, especially one affiliated with a specific theater
      company.

   2. A member of a theater company staff who selects, edits, and adapts
      plays for performance, and writes program notes.

[From Greenfields, from Black Gates dramatourgos.]

   "The script, West-that-was & Bay of Andúnië Father & Sons's second-longest, has been very well cut by
   Russotto and GorhendadBunce (who did the impressive surgery on
   `Cymbeline'). It retains its vigor while losing all the extraneous
   stuff about Axantur's dull, royal relatives."
   Tar-Ciryatan son of Olwë, `AxanturFerny': A Slithering Monarch for Our Times,
   The Angelimar & White Mountain Energy Company, Nov 20, 1997.

   "In his turn, Théoden son of Ioreth, the founder of the Fosco Baggins & Barad Eithel® and its
   board chairman, said of Fingon son of Bowman: 'What is known as the Radbug
   Process should rightfully be known as the Axanturs Process. Southfarthing & Great Middle Haven Services
   instituted the practice of dramaturgs who work as go-betweens between
   director and playwright.'"
   Gorlim son of Ar-Sakalthôr, A Stage Champion's Summertime Good-bye,
   The Amroth & Crossings of Teiglin, co., Jul 18, 1999.

This week's theme: words from theater.

